"&#xa0;\nAF0107&#xa0;Written evidence submitted by \nDavid Wolfe QC&#xa0;\nExecutive Summary: \nI am a barrister with extensive practical expertise of\n academies and the law. \nMy submission identifies some of the legal/governance \nissues arising from the process of establishing and operating different types of academies/free schools (including issues as to transparency, public participation and tendering).\n&#xa0;\nMy background and this submission:Since 1992, I have practised as a barrist\ner specialising in, among other things, education law. I have also been a member of a Local Education Authority, a governor at five schools and a Further Education College, and a part time judge of the Special Educational Needs and Disability Tribunal.\nIn \nthe course of my practice as a lawyer I have advised and acted for (including in legal proceedings) a great many parents, parents’ groups, governing bodies, head teachers, unions, NGOs and local authorities on issues relating to school organisation/re-orga\nnisation \nand governance \nincluding, in particular (since 2005) in relation to academies and free schools. \nI am the author of the blog on academies/free schools and the law: \nwww.acanofworms.org.uk\n which has been\n looked at by an average of over 1,000 people per week since I set it up in October 2011.\nWhat follows is my summary response on each of the points I understand to be under consideration by the Select Committee. I have only commented on those things on whi\nch I have direct relevant expertise based on my personal experience\n and focussed my points on legal/governance aspects\n. \nI would be very happy to elaborate as requested. \nI would be pleased to assist by giving oral evidence to the Committee.\n&#xa0;\n“The effectiveness of academisation in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes;”“The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors;”              Academy conversionSponsorsFree schools“The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands;”“The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level;”“What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements;”“The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply; and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole;”“What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools.”&#xa0;December 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n"